# Security Rules

## Mandatory Pre-Commit Checks
- [ ] No hardcoded secrets (API keys, passwords, tokens)
- [ ] All user inputs validated
- [ ] SQL injection prevention (parameterized queries)
- [ ] XSS prevention (sanitized HTML output)
- [ ] CSRF protection enabled where needed
- [ ] Authentication/authorization verified on protected routes
- [ ] Rate limiting on all endpoints
- [ ] Error messages don't leak sensitive data

## Secret Management
- NEVER hardcode secrets in source code
- ALWAYS use environment variables or a secret manager
- Validate required secrets are present at startup
- Rotate any secrets that may have been exposed

## Frontend Security
- Sanitize all user-generated HTML (DOMPurify)
- Use `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` ONLY with sanitized content
- Validate all form inputs client-side AND server-side
- Use `Content-Security-Policy` headers
- Enable `X-Frame-Options: DENY` or `SAMEORIGIN`

## Backend Security
- Use parameterized queries for ALL database operations
- Hash passwords with bcrypt/Argon2 (never MD5/SHA1)
- Implement JWT or session-based auth correctly
- Set secure cookie flags (`HttpOnly`, `Secure`, `SameSite`)
- Validate file uploads (type, size, content)
- Log security events (failed auth, suspicious activity)

## Docker Security
- Run containers as non-root user
- Use specific image tags (not `latest`)
- Scan images for vulnerabilities
- Keep secrets out of Docker layers (use BuildKit secrets)

## If Security Issue Found
1. STOP immediately
2. Assess scope and impact
3. Fix CRITICAL issues before continuing
4. Rotate any exposed secrets
5. Review entire codebase for similar issues
6. Document the fix and lessons learned
